## Theorem: amc12b_2020_p2

Theorem: amc12b_2020_p2
Variables: (100, ^, 2, -, 7, 2) (real)
Prove: ((100 ^ 2 - 7 ^ 2):ℝ) / (70 ^ 2 - 11 ^ 2) * ((70 - 11) * (70 + 11) / ((100 - 7) * (100 + 7))) = 1

Goal: ((100 ^ 2 - 7 ^ 2):ℝ) / (70 ^ 2 - 11 ^ 2) * ((70 - 11) * (70 + 11) / ((100 - 7) * (100 + 7))) = 1

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Both factors are the same difference-of-squares ratio written in inverse forms, so each simplifies to 1 by factoring and cancellation.",
  "plan": [
    "Rewrite each difference of squares using a^2-b^2=(a-b)(a+b).",
    "Cancel the common factors in the large product.",
    "Show that the remaining expression is 1."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "100^2 - 7^2 = (100-7)(100+7) and 70^2 - 11^2 = (70-11)(70+11).",
      "reasoning": "This is the standard difference-of-squares identity a^2-b^2=(a-b)(a+b), applied to the two differences appearing in the expression.",
      "facts_used": [
        "difference of squares"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The expression can be rewritten as ((100-7)(100+7)/(70^2-11^2)) * ((70-11)(70+11)/((100-7)(100+7))).",
      "reasoning": "Substitute the factorizations from step 1 into the original fraction and keep the second factor unchanged.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "After cancellation, the product equals 1.",
      "reasoning": "Using step 1 again, replace 70^2-11^2 by (70-11)(70+11). Then the first factor becomes (100-7)(100+7)/((70-11)(70+11)), which is exactly the reciprocal of the second factor. Their product is therefore 1.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 1",
        "multiplicative inverse property"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "1"
}

